  "prompt": "How do you determine the Lewis structure of SO2?",
  "response": "To determine the Lewis structure of sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082), follow these steps:\n\n1. **Count the total number of valence electrons**:\n   - Sulfur (S) is in group 16 of the periodic table, so it has 6 valence electrons.\n   - Each oxygen (O) atom also has 6 valence electrons, and there are two oxygen atoms.\n   - Total valence electrons = 6 (from S) + 2 \u00d7 6 (from 2 O) = 6 + 12 = 18 valence electrons.\n\n2. **Determine the central atom**:\n   - Sulfur is less electronegative than oxygen, so it will be the central atom. The structure will have sulfur in the center with the two oxygen atoms attached.\n\n3. **Draw initial bonds**:\n   - Connect each oxygen atom to the sulfur atom with a single bond. This uses 4 of the 18 electrons (2 electrons for each bond).\n   - At this point, you have 18 - 4 = 14 electrons remaining.\n\n4. **Distribute remaining electrons**:\n   - Place electron pairs to satisfy the octet rule for both oxygen atoms. Start by placing 6 electrons (3 lone pairs) around each oxygen atom.\n   - This uses up 12 of the remaining 14 electrons (6 for each O), leaving you with 2 electrons.\n\n5. **Check the octet**:\n   - At this stage, each oxygen has 8 electrons (6 from lone pairs and 2 from the single bond with sulfur), but sulfur only has 4 electrons (2 from each single bond).\n   - To satisfy the octet rule for sulfur, you can form double bonds with the oxygen atoms.\n\n6. **Form double bonds**:\n   - Change one lone pair from each oxygen into a bonding pair with sulfur. Each oxygen now forms a double bond with sulfur.\n   - This gives you two double bonds between sulfur and oxygen. Now sulfur has 8 electrons (4 from each double bond) and each oxygen has 8 electrons.\n\n7. **Final Lewis structure**:\n   - The final Lewis structure for SO\u2082 has sulfur in the center with two double bonds to oxygen atoms, and each oxygen has 2 lone pairs.\n   - The structure can be represented as:\n     ```\n        O\n       //\n      S\n       \\\n        O\n     ```\n   - Each atom has satisfied the octet rule, making this a stable configuration.\n\nIn summary, the Lewis structure for SO\u2082 features sulfur double bonded to two oxygen atoms, which each have two lone pairs of electrons.",
